1
00:01:49,810 --> 00:01:53,440
The tank itself was unusual
in that it was vertical...

2
00:01:53,610 --> 00:01:55,530
...and looked like an old boiler.

3
00:01:56,150 --> 00:01:58,700
Inside the tank,
the subject wore a heavy glass bubble.

4
00:01:58,860 --> 00:02:02,370
You would have thought the whole
contraption uncomfortable to say the least.

5
00:02:02,530 --> 00:02:03,990
It was, however, effective.

6
00:02:04,620 --> 00:02:08,750
Of the 23 students tested,
only two found the experience unpleasant.

7
00:02:08,920 --> 00:02:13,290
Some even called it exhilarating.
A number of students hallucinated.

8
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:17,590
Dr. Jessup found the encephalographic
evidence especially interesting.

9
00:02:17,880 --> 00:02:21,140
And one Saturday afternoon,
in April 1967...

10
00:02:21,300 --> 00:02:24,300
...he decided to try
the experience for himself.

11
00:03:52,060 --> 00:03:54,560
Arthur. Hey, Arthur.

12
00:03:55,650 --> 00:03:57,480
Are you there?

13
00:03:57,650 --> 00:03:59,820
Can you hear me, Arthur?

14
00:04:01,240 --> 00:04:03,240
Arthur, answer me.

15
00:04:03,990 --> 00:04:06,910
Is that it? You want me
to come in and get you out?

16
00:04:07,950 --> 00:04:09,370
Yeah.

17
00:04:10,660 --> 00:04:12,750
I want to get a look at those EEG tracings.

18
00:05:02,710 --> 00:05:04,880
All right. How do you feel?

19
00:05:05,050 --> 00:05:06,550
Not bad.

20
00:05:06,720 --> 00:05:09,300
I hallucinated like a son of a bitch.

21
00:05:09,470 --> 00:05:12,350
A variety of dream states,
mystical states.

22
00:05:12,520 --> 00:05:15,020
A lot of religious allegory,
mostly out of Revelation.

23
00:05:15,180 --> 00:05:17,190
You were in there close to five hours.

24
00:05:17,350 --> 00:05:20,150
- Lt felt like an hour.
- Ý'd like to try that myself sometime.

25
00:05:20,320 --> 00:05:21,770
You should. You'll like it.

26
00:05:25,530 --> 00:05:27,240
Did we have any communication?

27
00:05:27,410 --> 00:05:30,530
Oh, sure. L kept checking you out
like you told me to.

28
00:05:31,030 --> 00:05:32,120
How'd l respond?

29
00:05:33,200 --> 00:05:36,040
Very orderly.
At one point you were crying.

30
00:05:36,210 --> 00:05:37,410
You mean actually crying?

31
00:05:37,580 --> 00:05:39,790
You were sobbing.
There were tears on your face.

32
00:05:39,960 --> 00:05:42,380
When I asked you what was going on...

33
00:05:42,550 --> 00:05:46,130
...you said you were re-experiencing
your father's death.

34
00:05:48,050 --> 00:05:50,930
- Did you make notes?
- Lt's all there.

35
00:05:51,100 --> 00:05:52,850
I'd like to try this again next week.

36
00:05:53,010 --> 00:05:55,270
Do you think you could make it again
next week?

37
00:05:55,930 --> 00:05:57,930
What are we looking for?

38
00:05:58,350 --> 00:06:01,940
I don't know, yet.

39
00:06:02,940 --> 00:06:05,860
There's really very little literature
on this kind of research.

40
00:06:06,030 --> 00:06:09,150
There's some good people in the field,
Tart, Ornstein and Deikman...

41
00:06:09,320 --> 00:06:12,530
...but most of it is radical-hip stuff,
drug-culture apologias.

42
00:06:12,700 --> 00:06:15,910
Obviously, the first thing to do
is set up some sensible methodology.

43
00:06:16,080 --> 00:06:18,830
Study these experiences
under controlled conditions.

44
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:21,630
It won't interfere with the work
we're doing with Hobart.

45
00:06:21,790 --> 00:06:25,130
What are we getting into? A new
sensory deprivation? Ýsolation studies?

46
00:06:25,300 --> 00:06:27,300
Where will we be going
with the tank stuff?

47
00:06:27,470 --> 00:06:30,340
We're not writing up a grant.
Strictly bootlegging, for kicks.

48
00:06:30,510 --> 00:06:32,510
As long as we've got
the use of this tank...

49
00:06:32,680 --> 00:06:35,720
...let's play around with it.
Let's find out where it takes us.

50
00:06:35,890 --> 00:06:39,520
It's fascinating stuff, Arthur.
I think we ought to get into it.

51
00:06:40,980 --> 00:06:44,360
I didn't even know they had one of those
isolation tanks at New York Hospital.

52
00:06:44,520 --> 00:06:46,730
Must be some guy
in the psychology department...

53
00:06:46,900 --> 00:06:49,190
...doing sensory deprivation studies.

54
00:06:49,360 --> 00:06:51,700
What's Jessup doing with it?

55
00:06:53,070 --> 00:06:55,700
You've got me. He's been taking students
out of his classes and testing them.

56
00:06:55,870 --> 00:06:57,870
He's been doing this
for three, four months.

57
00:06:59,250 --> 00:07:00,790
- Did you know...
Arthur.

58
00:07:00,960 --> 00:07:03,330
...Jessup was into this stuff?
- Not until you told me.

59
00:07:03,500 --> 00:07:05,290
Arthur?
- What do you want, honey?

60
00:07:05,460 --> 00:07:08,130
How long are you going to let it ring?

61
00:07:08,630 --> 00:07:10,050
It's okay, I'll get it.

62
00:07:10,220 --> 00:07:12,130
He's the last guy
to be screwing around...

63
00:07:12,300 --> 00:07:15,100
...with anything as flaky
as altered states of consciousness.

64
00:07:15,260 --> 00:07:19,520
Well, let's face it.
Jessup is pretty flaky himself.

65
00:07:21,690 --> 00:07:23,440
That's him.

66
00:07:43,460 --> 00:07:47,000
Arthur says you're very shy.
He wants me to draw you out.

67
00:07:47,170 --> 00:07:49,800
Draw me out?
That doesn't sound like Arthur.

68
00:07:49,960 --> 00:07:53,630
Well, what he actually said was
you were a high-handed, arrogant prick.

69
00:07:53,800 --> 00:07:55,640
A little nuts, but brilliant...

70
00:07:55,800 --> 00:07:59,220
...and that if l ever got you talking,
I would find you fascinating.

71
00:07:59,390 --> 00:08:01,060
That sounds more like Arthur.

72
00:08:01,230 --> 00:08:03,440
He says you're doing some work
at Payne Whitney.

73
00:08:03,600 --> 00:08:06,400
- Yes.
- What sort of work?

74
00:08:06,560 --> 00:08:09,900
Toxic metabolite stuff, replicating
Heath's and Friedhoff's strategies...

75
00:08:10,070 --> 00:08:12,740
...to find maverick substances
specific to schizophrenia.

76
00:08:12,900 --> 00:08:14,990
We're chasing our tails. What do you do?

77
00:08:15,160 --> 00:08:17,910
I'm a physical anthropologist,
sweating out my dissertation.

78
00:08:18,080 --> 00:08:19,990
- Where?
- Columbia.

79
00:08:20,160 --> 00:08:22,290
Holloway and that bunch.

80
00:08:22,460 --> 00:08:24,830
You're kind of young for a Ph.D.,
aren't you?

81
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:27,210
- Ý'm 24.
- That's still pretty good.

82
00:08:27,380 --> 00:08:32,550
I didn't get my Ph.D. until
I was 25 and I'm supposed to be a whiz kid.

83
00:08:32,970 --> 00:08:34,010
I'm a whiz kid, too.

84
00:08:39,510 --> 00:08:42,640
Anthropology seems to attract
good-looking women.

85
00:08:44,890 --> 00:08:49,770
So you don't think schizophrenia can be
reduced to a single etiological agent?

86
00:08:50,440 --> 00:08:52,400
I'm not even sure it's a disease.

87
00:08:52,570 --> 00:08:55,530
You think madness is simply
another state of consciousness?

88
00:08:55,700 --> 00:08:58,450
There's a body of evidence
to support that.

89
00:08:59,990 --> 00:09:02,290
You don't like to talk
about your work, do you?

90
00:09:02,450 --> 00:09:04,450
As a rule, no.

91
00:09:08,960 --> 00:09:11,380
I've always been interested
in interior experiences.

92
00:09:11,550 --> 00:09:13,000
Especially religious experience.

93
00:09:13,170 --> 00:09:15,260
The reason I'm working
with schizophrenics...

94
00:09:15,420 --> 00:09:19,760
...is that religious experience
is so significant in schizophrenia.

95
00:09:19,930 --> 00:09:21,970
There's only so much
you can do with animals.

96
00:09:22,140 --> 00:09:25,020
Monkeys can't tell you what's going on
in their consciousness.

97
00:09:25,180 --> 00:09:26,980
You need human beings for that.

98
00:09:27,140 --> 00:09:30,860
You're not allowed to ablate humans,
you can't stick electrodes in their skulls.

99
00:09:31,020 --> 00:09:33,480
I have to use some kind
of trance-inducing technique.

100
00:09:33,650 --> 00:09:36,030
The isolation tank
seemed the least risky. Listen...

101
00:09:36,200 --> 00:09:39,660
... I'd like to go home with you tonight.
Would that be all right with you?

102
00:09:40,830 --> 00:09:44,790
I've got a roommate.
We'll be confined to the living-room couch.

103
00:09:45,500 --> 00:09:47,620
What's wrong
with the living-room couch?

104
00:09:47,790 --> 00:09:50,380
You tend to slip off a lot.

105
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:52,840
I'm sure we'll manage.

106
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:54,920
Yeah, I'm sure we will.

107
00:09:58,090 --> 00:10:01,430
So whenever you want to go there,
you let me know.

108
00:10:02,890 --> 00:10:04,850
- How about right now?
- Heh.

109
00:10:19,360 --> 00:10:21,070
What are you thinking about?

110
00:10:21,660 --> 00:10:22,660
God.

111
00:10:25,040 --> 00:10:26,450
Jesus, crucifixions.

112
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:32,130
As a rule, do you usually think about...

113
00:10:32,290 --> 00:10:35,090
...Christ and crucifixions
under sexual stress?

114
00:10:42,260 --> 00:10:45,600
When I was 9 years old,
I used to see visions.

115
00:10:45,890 --> 00:10:49,520
Visions of saints and angels,
even Christ himself.

116
00:10:52,440 --> 00:10:54,860
Of course, I don't do that anymore.

117
00:10:59,200 --> 00:11:01,610
Not since I was 16.

118
00:11:02,030 --> 00:11:03,370
Were your parents religious?

119
00:11:04,490 --> 00:11:06,120
Anything but.

120
00:11:06,290 --> 00:11:10,210
My father was an aeronautical engineer.
My mother, a clinical psychologist.

121
00:11:10,370 --> 00:11:11,920
What happened?

122
00:11:12,080 --> 00:11:16,130
I mean, how did a little kid who saw
visions of Christ turn into a physiologist...

123
00:11:16,300 --> 00:11:19,710
...teaching at the Cornell Medical College?
- L stopped believing.

124
00:11:20,470 --> 00:11:21,590
It was very dramatic.

125
00:11:21,760 --> 00:11:26,760
My father died a protracted
and painful death of cancer.

126
00:11:28,060 --> 00:11:30,730
I was 16 years old
and very fond of my father.

127
00:11:30,890 --> 00:11:34,230
I used to race to the hospital
every day after school...

128
00:11:34,400 --> 00:11:36,940
...and sit in his room doing my homework.

129
00:11:37,110 --> 00:11:39,280
He was very heavily sedated.

130
00:11:39,440 --> 00:11:42,150
The last few weeks he was in coma.

131
00:11:45,450 --> 00:11:47,620
One day l thought
I heard him say something.

132
00:11:48,950 --> 00:11:51,120
I got up and leaned over him...

133
00:11:51,290 --> 00:11:53,120
...my ear an inch away from his lips.

134
00:11:54,500 --> 00:11:56,670
"Did you say something, Pop?"

135
00:11:59,380 --> 00:12:03,130
Then l heard the word he was desperately
trying to say, a soft hiss of a word.

136
00:12:03,300 --> 00:12:05,090
He was saying:

137
00:12:08,140 --> 00:12:09,430
"Terrible."

138
00:12:17,980 --> 00:12:19,650
"Terrible."

139
00:12:22,280 --> 00:12:25,610
So the end was terrible,
even for the good people like my father.

140
00:12:25,780 --> 00:12:29,410
So the purpose of all our suffering
was just more suffering.

141
00:12:31,910 --> 00:12:36,500
By dinnertime, l had dispensed with God
altogether. I never saw another vision.

142
00:12:40,630 --> 00:12:43,590
I haven't told anybody
about this in 10 years.

143
00:12:46,260 --> 00:12:48,850
I'm telling you now
because l want you to know...

144
00:12:49,010 --> 00:12:52,470
...what sort of a nut
you might be getting mixed up with.

145
00:12:54,520 --> 00:12:56,600
Arthur was right.

146
00:12:56,850 --> 00:12:59,770
You are a fascinating bastard.

147
00:14:01,590 --> 00:14:05,380
Dad! Dad! Dad!

148
00:15:28,880 --> 00:15:30,340
- Hi.
- Hi.

149
00:15:30,510 --> 00:15:31,630
Well, it's settled.

150
00:15:31,800 --> 00:15:35,350
Metcalfe spoke to Spencer this morning
and it's definite. The job's mine.

151
00:15:35,510 --> 00:15:38,180
I'll be in Nairobi doing
my post-doc work July and August.

152
00:15:38,350 --> 00:15:40,480
And in September,
I'll be teaching at Harvard.

153
00:15:40,640 --> 00:15:41,850
Terrific.

154
00:15:43,190 --> 00:15:46,020
So looks like we'll both be teaching
at Harvard in September.

155
00:15:46,190 --> 00:15:48,020
Looks that way.

156
00:15:49,570 --> 00:15:53,150
Well, you can't get any tidier
than that, can you?

157
00:15:55,280 --> 00:15:58,910
We're gonna be together in Boston,
and l think we should get married.

158
00:16:01,160 --> 00:16:04,120
You know, of course,
I'm supposed to be a little bit nuts.

159
00:16:04,290 --> 00:16:07,000
A little bit?
You're an unmitigated madman.

160
00:16:09,340 --> 00:16:13,720
You don't have to tell me how weird
you are. I know how weird you are.

161
00:16:13,880 --> 00:16:15,930
I'm the girl in your bed
the past two months.

162
00:16:16,100 --> 00:16:20,600
Even sex is a mystical experience
for you. You carry on like a flagellant...

163
00:16:20,770 --> 00:16:24,640
...which can be very nice, but l sometimes
wonder if it's me that's being made love to.

164
00:16:24,810 --> 00:16:28,650
I feel like I'm being harpooned by some
raging monk in the act of receiving God.

165
00:16:32,320 --> 00:16:34,900
And you are a Faust-freak, Eddie.

166
00:16:35,070 --> 00:16:38,740
You'd sell your soul
to find the great truth.

167
00:16:38,910 --> 00:16:42,080
Well, human life
doesn't have great truths.

168
00:16:42,250 --> 00:16:45,790
We're born in doubt. We spend our lives
persuading ourselves we're alive.

169
00:16:45,960 --> 00:16:49,090
And one way we do that is
we love each other, like I love you.

170
00:16:49,550 --> 00:16:51,840
I can't imagine living without you.

171
00:16:52,550 --> 00:16:56,760
So let's get married, and if it turns out
to be a disaster, it'll be a disaster.

172
00:16:56,930 --> 00:16:59,100
We'll shake hands and say good-bye.

173
00:17:06,400 --> 00:17:08,100
He's giving her dimethyltryptamine.

174
00:17:08,270 --> 00:17:12,440
It takes effect in about a minute
and she'll trip out for about half an hour.

175
00:17:18,370 --> 00:17:20,450
Do you feel different now?

176
00:17:20,700 --> 00:17:21,780
Yes.

177
00:17:21,950 --> 00:17:23,700
Less anxious?

178
00:17:24,160 --> 00:17:25,290
Much less.

179
00:17:25,460 --> 00:17:27,460
Do you have any special feelings?

180
00:17:27,620 --> 00:17:28,920
I feel...

181
00:17:29,630 --> 00:17:32,840
...like my heart
is being touched by Christ.

182
00:17:48,310 --> 00:17:51,650
There's a lot of religious delusion
among acute schizophrenics.

183
00:17:51,820 --> 00:17:55,030
Some say schizophrenics
are physically different from the rest of us.

184
00:17:55,190 --> 00:17:58,530
It's almost as if they were trying
to change their physical selves...

185
00:17:58,700 --> 00:18:01,530
...to adapt to their schizophrenic image
of themselves.

186
00:18:09,670 --> 00:18:13,130
All right, we'll get married,
since it's that important to you.

187
00:18:13,710 --> 00:18:15,340
I'm not comfortable with women...

188
00:18:15,510 --> 00:18:18,670
...and I'm not likely to find anyone
half as remarkable as you again.

189
00:18:20,180 --> 00:18:23,260
I think I can make
a reasonably good husband.

190
00:18:25,100 --> 00:18:27,020
I don't want to lose you, you see.

191
00:18:28,940 --> 00:18:31,810
I suppose that's the closest thing
to a declaration of love...

192
00:18:31,980 --> 00:18:33,900
...that l will ever get out of you.

193
00:18:45,540 --> 00:18:47,700
Am l really that weird in bed?

194
00:18:47,870 --> 00:18:49,710
Sometimes.

195
00:18:51,210 --> 00:18:53,080
Shall l try to change?

196
00:18:53,250 --> 00:18:55,710
No, I kind of like it.

197
00:19:19,070 --> 00:19:21,360
Daddy, I'm tired.
We'll give the lady a ride.

198
00:19:21,530 --> 00:19:23,820
- Whoa! Oh!
Hey, Mason, be careful.

199
00:19:24,530 --> 00:19:27,950
How you doing, Eddie?
- Hi, Mason. How about a beer?

200
00:19:33,250 --> 00:19:36,750
- Lf I didn't see this, l wouldn't believe it.
- You weren't supposed to be here.

201
00:19:36,920 --> 00:19:40,300
Hi, what's your name?
My name's Mason Parrish. This is Margaret.

202
00:19:40,470 --> 00:19:42,970
Mason, Arthur Rosenberg
I'm always telling you about.

203
00:19:43,140 --> 00:19:46,140
- How are you?
- Mason Parrish, nice to meet you.

204
00:19:49,350 --> 00:19:52,770
Look at the family man.
Oh, why, Eddie, you look so wonderful.

205
00:19:52,940 --> 00:19:55,860
I don't believe it.
Not again. When did this happen?

206
00:19:56,020 --> 00:19:58,110
- Lt's a long story.
- You look wonderful.

207
00:19:58,280 --> 00:19:59,860
Have you found a place yet?

208
00:20:00,030 --> 00:20:02,280
We got a nice little place
near Huntington Field.

209
00:20:02,450 --> 00:20:04,950
It's been seven years
since we moved to San Francisco.

210
00:20:05,120 --> 00:20:08,030
Arthur's gonna to teach at Boston U.
Eddie's been telling me.

211
00:20:08,200 --> 00:20:10,080
I hear you just got associate professor.

212
00:20:10,250 --> 00:20:12,750
You guys must be loaded.
Two professors in one family.

213
00:20:12,920 --> 00:20:15,460
We've got a place in Maine
you can use for the summer.

214
00:20:15,630 --> 00:20:17,880
I'm going to Africa again.
Eddie'll be in Mexico.

215
00:20:18,050 --> 00:20:20,630
You know a guy named Eccheverria,
University of Mexico?

216
00:20:20,800 --> 00:20:23,550
- He worked with you in California.
- Sure. Bright young guy.

217
00:20:23,720 --> 00:20:26,390
He's here at the museum.
We'll all have to get together.

218
00:20:26,550 --> 00:20:28,800
I'm going back to Mexico
with him in June.

219
00:20:28,970 --> 00:20:29,970
What's in Mexico?

220
00:20:30,140 --> 00:20:33,480
Eccheverria's got this witch doctor
down there, the Hinchi Indians.

221
00:20:33,640 --> 00:20:37,360
They're an isolated tribe in Central Mexico
who practice ancient Toltec rituals.

222
00:20:37,520 --> 00:20:39,940
Sacred mushroom ceremonies,
that kind of thing.

223
00:20:40,110 --> 00:20:42,610
Apparently they use some kind
of hallucinatory drug...

224
00:20:42,780 --> 00:20:46,240
...that is supposed to evoke
a common experience in all users.

225
00:20:46,410 --> 00:20:49,530
Maggie's fallen asleep on the couch.
Will you take care of her?

226
00:20:49,700 --> 00:20:51,080
Sure.

227
00:20:51,250 --> 00:20:53,790
Did you ever get into an isolation tank
since New York?

228
00:20:53,960 --> 00:20:55,250
No. Did you?

229
00:20:55,420 --> 00:20:58,080
No, but they've got one here
at the medical school.

230
00:20:58,250 --> 00:21:00,880
I didn't think anybody was doing
those studies anymore.

231
00:21:01,050 --> 00:21:03,550
We did interesting stuff
in that tank in New York...

232
00:21:03,720 --> 00:21:05,510
...for the months we played with it.

233
00:21:05,680 --> 00:21:08,430
Maybe when l get back from Mexico
we'll get into it again.

234
00:21:08,600 --> 00:21:10,350
Why not.

235
00:21:18,730 --> 00:21:21,360
A terrific housekeeper she's not.

236
00:21:22,820 --> 00:21:24,990
- They're getting a divorce, you know.
- Who?

237
00:21:25,150 --> 00:21:28,070
- L don't know if they're actually-
- What are you talking about?

